Date: Thu 5 Feb 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmmail.org>
Source: Reuters News UK online, Thu 5 Feb 2004 [edited]
<http://www.reuters.co.uk/newsArticle.jhtml?type=healthNews&storyID=4288525Â§ion=news>

More Suspected Human Cases in Thailand and Viet Nam
---------------------------------------------------
The human death toll from the avian influenza epidemic sweeping through
Asian poultry flocks rose to 16 on Thu 5 Feb 2004 as China, a major focus
of concern, admitted it faced a tough fight to defeat the disease. "Some
parts of our animal disease prevention system are weak and vulnerable, and
the public has limited knowledge about the disease and ways to prevent it,"
China's Agriculture Ministry said. "It remains an arduous task for China to
prevent and control the disease," it said in a statement before a news
conference.
The confession from China, castigated in 2003 for covering up the SARS
outbreak for several months, came as Viet Nam said a 16-year-old southern
girl had become its 11th bird flu victim. "We have conducted tests in our
hospital, and the results showed the girl from Soc Trang province had died
from avian influenza virus infection," Tran Tinh Hien, deputy director of
the Hospital for Tropical Diseases in Ho Chi Minh City, told Reuters. The
other 5 died in Thailand, which said it had 2 more suspected cases, a
2-year-old boy from Khon Kaen province, northeast of Bangkok, and a
67-year-old man from the central province of Chainat. Thailand, which also
has another 2 probable avian influenza deaths, now has 19 suspected cases.
Vietnam and Thailand are alone among 10 countries hit by avian influenza to
have reported cases in humans, and almost all of them came from direct
contact with infected chickens. But experts say there is a remote chance
the virulent avian influenza A (H5N1) virus could infect a person
[experiencing a human influenza virus infection] and create a new strain
[by reassortment], which could set off a pandemic in a world population
with no immunity to it. If that were to happen, China, which raised 8
billion chickens in 2003, mostly on small, cramped farms in close contact
with farmers, might well be the place, experts say.
12 of China's 31 provinces have confirmed or suspected outbreaks of avian
influenza, and the government said local officials had strict orders to
report any sign of human contagion promptly, openly, and fully -- echoing
what became Beijing's catch-phrase in its war on SARS after the initial
cover-up in 2003.
The Agriculture Ministry said more than 1.2 million chickens had been
culled in China, a small proportion of the 50 million poultry the U.N.'s
Food and Agriculture Organization estimates have been slaughtered [in the
region up to the present].
Thailand says it has culled 25.9 million poultry in mass slaughters the FAO
says are the most effective means of stamping the disease out.
Chief government spokesman Jakrapob Penkair said it was working. "Our
progress in fighting the disease is satisfactory," he told reporters. "The
situation is improving steadily." He said Thailand's "red zones" -- the
5-km (3-mile) area around a confirmed outbreak within which all poultry
must be slaughtered -- had dropped to 10 in 5 of its 76 provinces. Last
week, the government reported more than 140 red zones in 29 provinces. So
confident is it that the outbreak is under control, the Thai government is
organizing "chicken-eating fairs" across the country Saturday in a bid to
convince Thais that the experts are right to say well-cooked chicken and
eggs pose no danger.
[Byline: Jonathan Ansfield and Christina Toh-Pantin]
