Source: Xinhua News Agency, Thu 5 Feb 2004 [edited]
<http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/>

Viet Nam: Human-to-human Transmission Denied
--------------------------------------------
There has been no transmission of avian influenza virus among humans in
Viet Nam, Vietnamese Deputy Minister of Health Tran Chi Liem was quoted by
local media as saying on Thu 5 Feb 2004.
"The most [likely] way of transmission now is from wild birds to chickens
and then to persons," Liem said, adding that 3 deaths within a family in
northern Thai Binh province involve chickens, because all of the victims
directly slaughtered the fowls.
Klaus Stohr, head of the global influenza program of the World Health
Organisation (WHO), recently stated that the family members in Viet Nam
could have contacted directly to sick poultry, and that there has no
evidence of H5N1 being passed from person to person. According to Stohr,
the World Health Organisation is considering 3 possibilities: The avian
influenza A (H5N1) virus gradually mutates and transmits to humans easily;
viruses in poultry combine with human influenza viruses to form a new
strain that can spread globally; or that the avian influenza outbreak is
contained, posing no threat to people.
Vietnam reported a total of [119 confirmed and suspected influenza A virus
infections, including 15 cases of avian influenza A (H5N1) virus infection]
as of the afternoon of Wed 4 Feb 2004. However, "WHO has so far confirmed
only 13 cases [now revised to 15 -- see above part (1)] of H5N1 infections
in Viet Nam," Bob Dietz, spokesman of the organization in the country, told
Xinhua on Thu 5 Feb 2004.
